<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-hypothesis-in-linear-regression">Hyp=
othesis in Linear Regression</h2>



<p>Once you have fitted a straight line on the data, you need to ask, =E2=
=80=9C<strong>Is this straight line a significant fit for&nbsp;the data?</s=
trong>=E2=80=9D Or =E2=80=9CI<strong>s the</strong>&nbsp;<strong>beta coeff=
icient explain the&nbsp;variance in the data plotted?=E2=80=9D&nbsp;</stron=
g>And here comes the idea of&nbsp;<strong>hypothesis testing</strong>&nbsp;=
on the beta coefficient. The Null and Alternate hypotheses in this case are=
:</p>



<p>H 0 : B 1 &nbsp;=3D 0</p>



<p>H A : B 1 &nbsp;<strong>=E2=89=A0</strong>&nbsp;0</p>



<p>To test this hypothesis we use a&nbsp;<strong>t-test,&nbsp;</strong>test=
 statistics for the beta coefficient is given by,</p>


